Internet Capital Markets: The Next Big Thing?

AJC
Justin Baba
Chris Davis

May 16, 2025 ⋅  15 min read

Key Insights

  • Internet capital markets are emerging as a new onchain narrative, enabling creators, founders, and builders to tokenize products, concepts, or communities. This shift is accelerating capital formation across crypto and non-crypto sectors.
  • Believe’s breakout success has been the key driver behind this new narrative. With over $2 billion in volume and 15,000 tokens launched, the platform exemplifies how accessible asset issuance is powering a new wave of onchain experimentation.
  • Products launched on Believe span a surprising range of real-world applications, from social media tools to gaming and e-commerce. While many tokens remain speculative, a subset of projects are attempting to integrate tokens into functional user experiences.
  • The narrative remains highly polarizing, while proponents view internet capital markets as a breakthrough in permissionless capital formation, critics argue they primarily enable extractive speculation with little lasting value.
  • Internet capital markets will be successful if tokenized projects can deliver sustained utility, real revenue, and meaningful value accrual to holders. A single breakout product that ties token performance to genuine usage could catalyze broader validation.

Primer

A Breakout App Emerges

Onchain activity on Solana has surged back to life in recent weeks, fueled in part by the unexpected success of Believe, a novel token launchpad founded by Ben Pasternak. While token creation platforms are not new to crypto, Believe has captured the market’s attention by combining accessibility with effective curation. The premise is simple: anyone can launch a token directly from a post on X, but what sets Believe apart is the quality of the projects it has surfaced. Some of these projects include legitimate Web2 businesses with working products, a far cry from the low-effort meme coins and vaporware often associated with token launchpads. This higher standard of project quality has helped Believe attract a more serious cohort of builders and backers. Some notable projects launched via Believe include:

  • Dupe - Marketplace application for buying furniture and other user products.
  • CreatorBuddy - AI-powered growth tool for X.
  • Noodle - Onchain snake game where users risk money.
  • Giggles - Social media platform for short videos.
  • Fitted - AI-powered virtual closet for fashion items.

So far, Believe has been an incredible success. Nearly 15,000 tokens have been launched, generating close to $2 billion in total trading volume. The platform’s monetization model is equally compelling: Believe charges a 2% fee on every trade, with nearly $40 million in fees accrued to date, half of which goes back to token creators. This creator-aligned model has only amplified the ecosystem’s virality.

Unsurprisingly, Believe’s own token, LAUNCHCOIN, has been the main beneficiary of this success, peaking over a $300 million market cap. But perhaps more interesting than the success of any single platform is the broader narrative it has sparked: Internet Capital Markets.

Defining Internet Capital Markets

The idea is deceptively simple yet profoundly transformative: anyone can tokenize almost anything. Whether it’s a creator launching a social token, a startup raising capital via memecoins, or an app issuing shares onchain, the barriers to building tradable markets around ideas, personas, or products are collapsing. With tools like Believe, token creation and distribution are no longer restricted to seasoned developers or deep-pocketed founders. They’re available to anyone with a social following, a compelling pitch, or simply a meme that resonates.

This new class of capital formation doesn't resemble traditional equity markets, but rather, the internet: fast, permissionless, and chaotic. Value can now accrue not just to companies, but to concepts. Projects can bootstrap liquidity, community, and attention all at once, unlocking a new mode of internet-native entrepreneurship.

We asked Messari analysts (past and present) for their thoughts on the future of internet capital markets and what this shift in the meta means for the broader market.

The State of Onchain - Justin Baba

Justin Baba is a former Messari analyst who has graciously contributed his thoughts to this piece.

At its core, the internet capital markets meta is fueled by the same forces that caused the AI agent sector to reach a $10 billion market cap: asset creation tied to a product and speculation on a total addressable market beyond crypto. Crypto allowed AI agent creators to attach a token to their agent, similar to how Believe allows Web2 founders to easily launch a token associated with their product or company. This gives market participants the ability to speculate on the future performance of these products, often causing valuations to far exceed realistic expectations.

Speculation on the total addressable market of AI agents and internet capital markets was a significant driver for both sectors. AI agents had the potential to onboard people from the AI industry outside of crypto, while internet capital markets have the potential to bring Web2 businesses onchain. For internet capital markets, we have already seen working Web2 products, such as Dupe, launch tokens on Believe, igniting speculation that these launches could generate network effects beyond crypto, particularly in the consumer sector. The question now is whether these projects will be able to deliver value that can keep up with the speculation.

As we have seen with many other narratives, a majority of projects trend to zero as they fail to deliver value that matches the hype. This repeated cycle has led to shifting behavior among market participants, who are increasingly exhausted by unsustainable hype-driven runs. Many now enter trades with little belief and even less patience, as tokens are often launched, traded, and abandoned within days. A big reason for this shift is that the barrier to entry to create tokens has been drastically reduced due to platforms such as Pump.fun. For example, the average lifespan of a token from Pump.fun is 12 days, and 15% of the coins launched on there die within the first day. It is a hyper-financialized environment where narrative functions less as a mission and more as a pretext for capital rotation.

This speed has dramatically altered incentives for founders. They are now less motivated to build meaningful user experiences or long-term roadmaps, realizing that large amounts of money can be made in a short period simply by generating hype. Liquidity is frontloaded, price action is reflexive, and attention decays quickly. The result is an environment where it is easy for builders to extract as much value as possible, as fast as possible, often at the expense of the project’s long-term viability.

Now, market participants understand how these metas typically end. Reflexivity erodes any reason to be a long-term holder; the game has shifted to selling before the meta collapses. They’ve seen what happened to AI agent tokens once that narrative exhausted itself, and they don’t want to be caught in the same position with internet capital markets.

However, it’s still possible that this time is different, and that Internet Capital Markets can help reset sentiment in a more constructive direction. If any of the products launched via Believe are able to generate meaningful revenue and deliver tangible value back to tokenholders, a sustainable flywheel could emerge.

Evolving Past Speculation as the Use Case - AJC

One of the core reasons why internet capital markets are so fascinating is that they enable global speculation at scale. But while speculation itself is neither inherently good nor bad, it exists on a spectrum, from healthy to extractive.

  • “Healthy Speculation” occurs when an asset has some non-zero fundamental value (call it B). One trader believes its fair value is A, and another believes it’s C. As they trade, their opposing views contribute to price discovery, helping the market converge toward the asset’s true worth.
  • “Extractive Speculation,” on the other hand, involves assets with no inherent value. Trader #1 believes it's worth A, Trader #2 believes it's worth B, but in reality, the asset trends steadily toward zero. The result? A negative-sum game where capital is gradually siphoned away, often benefiting early insiders or platform operators at the expense of everyone else.

I’m not convinced that Believe is enabling healthy speculation, at least not yet. A few core issues stand out. While Believe has excelled at onboarding talented Web2 creators and founders, its technical product, the token launchpad, is lackluster. There’s nothing fundamentally unique about it, and in fact, it's inferior to alternatives due to its steep 2% fee per trade.

This introduces a conundrum: those high fees are the primary selling point for creators. But if the assets being traded lack intrinsic value, then this model becomes extractive by design. The fee structure accelerates the inevitable trend toward zero, leaving retail traders in the wreckage once the speculative froth evaporates.

More fundamentally, what exactly are the assets being traded on Believe? Do they have any real value? According to Believe’s own Builder Playbook, tokens “must never represent equity,” “not be marketed as investments,” and “should function like digital merchandise.” But what is the value of digital merchandise? Once again, it's tough to say. A few projects have shared tentative plans:

  • Dupe will use DUPE for rewards and purchase discounts.
  • Fitted will use FITCOIN for token-gated login, user rewards, exclusive apparel drops, and in-app transactions.
  • Suby plans to use $SUBY for no-fee crypto payments.
  • Creator Buddy intends to integrate BUDDY into its app and introduce a burn mechanism.

These use cases are a step in the right direction, gesturing toward utility even if that utility is still in its infancy. Token-gated access, in-app perks, and reward systems can deepen user engagement. But many of these token functions feel retrofitted, layered on after the fact rather than thoughtfully integrated into the product’s architecture.

This raises a critical question: Are these tokens essential to the user experience, or are they optional accessories designed to drive volume and speculation?

If it’s the latter, then Believe remains firmly in the realm of extractive speculation. Retail participants may enter with hopes of upside, but without sustainable, utility-driven demand, these tokens risk becoming little more than churn mechanisms in an attention-driven financial casino. Unlike startup equity, which can be underpinned by ownership rights and a right to cash flows, these tokens operate in a space that still lacks clear standards, protections, or economic frameworks.

To be clear, the rise of platforms like Believe isn't without merit. They dramatically lower the barrier to launching onchain assets and expand the creative frontier of crypto. But infrastructure primitives alone aren’t enough. If internet capital markets are to mature into a durable financial markets, not just another speculative meme, we must move beyond speculation as the dominant use case. That means designing tokens that are functionally necessary, economically sustainable, and transparently governed within their respective businesses, applications, or platforms.

Ultimately, I choose to remain optimistic. Believe has already demonstrated that it can attract high-quality builders and capture cultural attention. It’s taken an early, important step in making token creation more accessible and creator-aligned. With its growing user base, vibrant ecosystem, and the cultural momentum behind it, Believe is well-positioned to evolve. If the team can double down on utility, rethink fee alignment, and support the development of enduring token economies, it could become a cornerstone of the next phase of internet capital markets.

Meet the New Boss... Same as the Old Boss? - Chris Davis

Believe is the latest iteration in a long line of applications built around one of crypto’s core value propositions: creating new assets. To some, Believe is simply a new vehicle for speculating on valueless tokens. To others, it demonstrates the power of capital formation through permissionless, globally accessible “internet capital markets.” Any way you frame it, Believe follows a similar trajectory laid out by earlier asset issuance experiments, like Virtuals and friend.tech, and is likely to face similar challenges.

One of Believe's most interesting differentiators from past iterations is its go-to-market strategy, which focuses on onboarding a Web2-native supply side. In contrast to apps like friend.tech or time.fun, who focused on crypto-native supply, Believe is onboarding founders with a track record of delivering successful Web2 consumer products. As mentioned in the primer, they’ve executed this go-to-market well so far. If these founders are truly long-term-oriented and remain committed to growing their products, this strategy could have a huge positive impact on user acquisition and retention. If even one product goes viral, Believe could see rapid growth as users seek to get in early on the next breakout hit.

However, Believe’s ability to continue scaling supply will depend on several factors. First, it must sustain a level of trading volume high enough to provide sufficient early-stage capital to projects launching on the platform. If trading volume drops off a cliff and the economics no longer justify the risk of potentially alienating a Web2 customer base with a token, founders may choose to raise capital through more traditional means. Despite the promising early metrics, past examples have shown how quickly volume can drop off after an initial surge.

Another factor influencing supply-side growth is the value derived from attention. Believe’s method of curating its platform gives featured apps more visibility. As Abstract has recently shown, this mechanism can drive meaningful growth for selected projects. However, while it’s currently easy to stand out due to limited competition, that attention will fragment as more projects launch on the platform.

Given the historical pattern of many similar projects experiencing rapid growth followed by steep declines in engagement, I’d put higher odds on Believe being more of a short-term narrative than a long-term sustainable ecosystem. However, as noted, its early success in executing a unique go-to-market strategy provides meaningful hope for its future. Regardless of the platform's fate, I firmly believe that permissionless capital formation is a use case for crypto that has a strong product-market fit. And, the more "shots on goal" we take, the closer we come to realizing the ideal iteration in this design space.

The Most Important Network is Solana - Mike Kremer

“Think of it as a way for supporters to back your project – not a security,” but “Standard insider trading laws still apply.” It’s hard to take this seriously as anything more than the next hot meta. Without either legal clarity or the courage/folly to launch a product in spite of current legal limitations, we’re just doing memecoins again.

At least this time, if you burn your money on something like Dupe, you can get a discounted couch from Wayfair. The future of finance is finally here!

In the long term, I don’t expect Believe or any related projects to be anything except net value extractive. However, I think it’s best to swallow the disdain and look at the bigger picture. Solana is a technical marvel capable of consistently supporting an impressive amount of broadly distributed activity in the token and application markets. It’s also worth noting that the apps are getting pretty good. Believe, Moonshot, et al. are good-looking applications with smooth user experiences. Step by painful step, we’re getting better and better at abstracting away the complexities of the blockchain and building approachable applications.

Ryan Watkins (Messari alumni btw) points out the even bigger picture. Solana is the home of innovation. We’re well past the days of Solana “copying everything from Ethereum”. Now, metas start on Solana, then Base copies them, both leaving Ethereum far in the dust. Whatever comes after internet capital markets, expect it to happen on Solana first.

Same Same, but Different, but Still Same - Matthew Nay

Believe is the latest in a long line of speculative asset experiments in crypto, joining the ranks of ICOs, NFTs, and PumpFun. While it didn’t originate the internet capital markets thesis, it has done something arguably more important: exposed more users to what that future might look like. Each iteration has made onchain asset creation easier. We’ve gone from needing to write smart contracts to spinning up tokens by replying to tweets.

Credit where it’s due: the Believe team has shown that we are closer than ever to realizing the internet capital markets vision. For context, back in January, Solana handled over $36 billion in 24-hour volume during the TRUMP memecoin craze without experiencing any downtime, more than 10% of NASDAQ’s daily volume. That’s as strong a signal as one could ask for.

That said, Believe is still a novelty. Fun, yes - just like Pump.fun, but still a toy. The real breakthrough comes when this infrastructure starts serving companies with meaningful value. That’s where platforms like Opening Bell by Superstate come in. Opening Bell allows companies to issue SEC-registered shares directly on Solana, combining traditional regulatory compliance with all the benefits of blockchain-native assets: 24/7 trading, instant settlement, and seamless DeFi integration. The first issuer? SOL Strategies, a Canadian public company running a similar strategy to Michael Saylor’s Strategy, specifically on Solana.

Of course, there are still massive regulatory hurdles ahead before equities trade solely onchain and NASDAQ becomes a legacy system. That’s where the Solana Policy Institute (SPI) and its initiative Project Open come into play. Project Open proposes an SEC pilot to allow equity issuance and trading on public blockchains.

Solana is now pursuing the internet capital markets thesis on two fronts:

  1. Technical – building the infrastructure to make asset creation seamless.
  2. Policy – shaping the regulatory path to legitimacy.

It’s no longer just about speculative assets. It’s about re-architecting capital markets from the ground up.
